failed_job.message:
immutability of configuration causes user mistakes often

Many have been puzzled by the fact that loader and writer configurations
are immutable objects - we had many error reports where the problem was
that settings were not applied properly.

The presence of three classes to hold settings, in a subtly different
way, does not help - makes the situation worse actually.

This commit leaves Ontologyconfigurator as the only (mutable) class
wrapping ConfigurationOptions handling. Also sets up the groundwork to
allow OWLOntologyDocumentSource and OWLOntologyDocumentTarget to take
charge of local overrides - a step towards OWLOntologyManager relaxing
its death grip on load and save processes.

Update Bytecode.Compound to hold multiple blocks.

In order for Bytecode.If to have both a true and false branch, we need
to extend Bytecode.Compount to be able to hold multiple blocks.  This is now
complete and seems to be working pretty well.  There are definitely
opportunities for optimisation at the binary bytecode level.  For example, for
some bytecodes we know they only have one block (e.g. assert), but the format
includes a variable length array.

fix: support insert ... on conflict...update for reWriteBatchedInserts=true

pgjdbc will avoid rewriting the query if a bind is identified after values(...)

That is ON CONFLICT... DO update set x=? is NOT rewrite-compatible, and update set x='default' is rewrite-compatible

"reported" here: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47664889/jdbc-batch-operations-understanding/48349524?noredirect=1#comment84691562_48349524

failed_job.message:
Fix some stream leaks.

There's a few places where OkHttp could leak a connection that needed to be
closed. With our new connection pool model this is easier to find. This fixes
two specific problems:
 - too many redirects doesn't release the last used connection
 - interceptors that throw runtime exceptions don't release the connection

There are likely more situations. I have hacked together a small little test
harness to make finding these leaks easier; that's not included in this PR.
